re, and cinema studies, Schwartz argues that "spectacular realities" are part of the foundation of modern mass society. She refutes the notion that modern life produced an unending parade of distractions leading to alienation, and instead suggests that crowds gathered not as dislocated spectators but as members of a new kind of crowd, one united in pleasure rather than protest.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEuropean. 4aGeneral. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh1 aSchwartz, Vanessa R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052022168040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092420840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924208/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles